    <item>
      <title></title>
      <link>https://ekaschalk.github.io/post/shell-font-lock/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://ekaschalk.github.io/post/shell-font-lock/</guid>
      <description>Font locking the Shell Prompt   This simple-sounding feature is involved and perhaps worth a post all its own.  I&amp;#39;m not sure if any shells besides python implement this feature. For example, type (let ...) in ielm and the let won&amp;#39;t be highlighted.  Buffers taking from comint-mode will not highlight the current prompt. Once entered, the prompt output will switch to the comint-highlight-input face.  We can&amp;#39;t enable font-lock-mode for inferior-hy-mode as otherwise the highlight input face will be overwritten, output will be colored (undesirable), and colors outputted by the shell (like for errors) will be overwritten.</description>
    </item>
    
